or even the nipples.

221
00:12:36,495 --> 00:12:40,402
Try using some petroleum
jelly on the affected areas."

222
00:13:00,116 --> 00:13:02,171
Oh, gosh!

223
00:13:16,918 --> 00:13:19,181
Dude, you are a
terrific runner.

224
00:13:19,768 --> 00:13:24,151
Tomorrow you're gonna run and
finish the New York City Marathon!

225
00:13:24,908 --> 00:13:26,890
You're the best.

226
00:13:27,066 --> 00:13:29,140
You look good.

227
00:13:29,787 --> 00:13:32,340
Nobody does it better than you.

228
00:13:32,355 --> 00:13:34,392
Marshall? Oh, my God!

229
00:13:35,637 --> 00:13:37,620
So, yes, it was your fault.

230
00:13:37,635 --> 00:13:39,902
I mean, if you don't show up at the
apartment in the middle of the day,

231
00:13:39,936 --> 00:13:42,590
Marshall doesn't break his toe,
Barney doesn't run in his place,

232
00:13:42,606 --> 00:13:44,660
I don't jump the turnstile
and get a court date,

233
00:13:44,696 --> 00:13:46,723
and we make our flight
in plenty of time!

234
00:13:48,785 --> 00:13:51,601
And I don't fall down and bite
my tongue at the airport.

235
00:13:51,747 --> 00:13:53,690
That really wasn't my fault.

236
00:13:53,705 --> 00:13:55,951
I wouldn't have walked in on
Marshall if it weren't for Lily.

237
00:13:55,967 --> 00:13:57,862
Hey, think about it.

238
00:13:58,107 --> 00:14:01,421
Hey, what's going on here?
Oh, looks like they're
camping out for something.

239
00:14:01,435 --> 00:14:02,751
Yeah, but for what?

240
00:14:02,767 --> 00:14:05,592
I don't know. Usually there's a
Stormtrooper or Klingon in line

241
00:14:07,205 --> 00:14:09,551
"Annual wedding dress blowout.

242
00:14:09,568 --> 00:14:12,721
Designer sample
dresses up to 90% off.

243
00:14:12,735 --> 00:14:15,791
Doors open tomorrow, 8:00 a.m."

244
00:14:15,808 --> 00:14:18,930
Oh, my God. Can you believe what some
nut bags will do to save a few bucks?

245
00:14:19,075 --> 00:14:21,090
We have to camp out.

246
00:14:21,128 --> 00:14:22,973
- Are you serious?
- You don't understand.

247
00:14:22,985 --> 00:14:25,390
This is an amazing sale.
I've heard about it before,

248
00:14:25,408 --> 00:14:27,392
but I never knew where it was.

249
00:14:27,406 --> 00:14:31,000
We'll have a wedding dress campout.
It'll be fun.

250
00:14:31,396 --> 00:14:33,472
I can't go.
I've got this thing.

251
00:14:33,486 --> 00:14:35,660
- What thing?
- A penis.

252
00:14:36,556 --> 00:14:38,770
- This is the place.
- Oh, wow.

253
00:14:39,385 --> 00:14:42,261
Badgley Mischka! Melissa Sweet!

254
00:14:42,276 --> 00:14:43,741
Vera Wang!

255
00:14:43,755 --> 00:14:47,822
Oh, Robin, do you have any idea
what you guys stumbled onto here?

256
00:14:47,855 --> 00:14:49,683
You said wang.

257
00:14:51,537 --> 00:14:55,991
Oh, this reminds me of the ticket
line to Lilith Fair, 1998.

258
00:14:56,008 --> 00:14:57,801
Only fewer mullets.

259
00:14:57,817 --> 00:15:02,593
You should feel good. You're only, like,
the tenth craziest bride in New York.

260
00:15:05,586 --> 00:15:07,533
Ooh, this is comfy.

261
00:15:07,546 --> 00:15:10,001
We might actually
be able to sleep.

262
00:15:11,197 --> 00:15:13,101
That's kind of annoying.

263
00:15:13,136 --> 00:15:17,371
Well, I'm sure somebody will be
out here to turn it off any minute.

264
00:15:19,681 --> 00:15:23,748
5 часа по-късно

265
00:15:29,905 --> 00:15:32,012
I don't think I can take this.

266
00:15:32,355 --> 00:15:37,471
Every time it turns off,
I think,
oh, maybe it won't
turn on again,

267
00:15:37,735 --> 00:15:39,702
but then it does.

268
00:15:39,715 --> 00:15:43,421
Why does it, Robin?
Why does it keep turning on?

269
00:15:43,436 --> 00:15:45,471
It's gonna be okay,
sweetie. Why...

270
00:15:45,487 --> 00:15:48,251
Why don't we make a
game out of it, okay?

271
00:15:48,267 --> 00:15:50,220
Why don't we sing along?

272
00:16:03,408 --> 00:16:07,347
3 часа по-късно

273
00:16:10,658 --> 00:16:12,550
If we get through this,

274
00:16:12,597 --> 00:16:16,031
I swear I'm gonna live
my life differently.

275
00:16:16,637 --> 00:16:20,341
I just want to tell my parents
I love them one more time.

276
00:16:21,696 --> 00:16:23,641
Morning, ladies.

277
00:16:24,867 --> 00:16:28,602
- It's him. It's the car guy!
- Get out of here!

278
00:16:37,756 --> 00:16:41,243
<i>The next morning, Robin was too tired
to go all the way back to Brooklyn,</i>

279
00:16:41,255 --> 00:16:43,071
<i>so while I was at work,</i>

280
00:16:43,085 --> 00:16:45,551
<i>she went to crash at my
apartment for a couple hours,</i>

281
00:16:45,636 --> 00:16:47,472
<i>and that's when...</i>

282
00:16:47,588 --> 00:16:49,951
Nobody does it better than you.

283
00:16:49,966 --> 00:16:52,013
Marshall?! Oh, my God!

284
00:16:53,176 --> 00:16:56,173
So if Lily hadn't dragged me
down to the wedding dress store,

285
00:16:56,188 --> 00:16:57,881
we would have made
the first flight.

286
00:16:57,936 --> 00:17:00,570
Oh, thank God.
The doors are still open. We made it.

287
00:17:00,715 --> 00:17:04,681
Hi. Please.
We really need to get on this flight.

288
00:17:04,795 --> 00:17:06,751
Oh, my God!

289
00:17:06,768 --> 00:17:09,183
You're that reporter
from Metro News 1.

290
00:17:09,196 --> 00:17:10,822
Yes, yes, I am.

291
00:17:10,858 --> 00:17:12,922
I can't believe
you recognized me.

292
00:17:12,935 --> 00:17:15,630
- You did that story on the giant pizzas?
- Would you check to see

293
00:17:15,665 --> 00:17:17,763
- if you have any more seats?
- One moment, sir.

294
00:17:18,218 --> 00:17:20,643
Were those pizzas real?
Come on, were they?

295
00:17:20,977 --> 00:17:22,882
- Robin...
- One second, Ted.

296
00:17:22,898 --> 00:17:24,960
Um, you know,
a lot of people ask me that.

297
00:17:24,977 --> 00:17:27,290
The truth is,
the pizzas were real.

298
00:17:27,306 --> 00:17:30,370
- Calzones. Trick photography.
- I knew it!

299
00:17:30,386 --> 00:17:33,371
God, it is so nice
to meet a fan!

300
00:17:33,776 --> 00:17:36,400
And I would be a fan of your
work if you could get us

301
00:17:36,416 --> 00:17:38,401
two seats on that next flight.

302
00:17:38,416 --> 00:17:42,961
Well, the, uh, flight attendants are
just finishing up their final
seat count.

303
00:17:43,155 --> 00:17:45,203
Let me see what I can find out.

304
00:17:45,216 --> 00:17:47,933
Would it help if I got on and gave an
impassioned speech about my destiny?

305
00:17:47,968 --> 00:17:49,973
I think it might hurt.

306
00:17:52,726 --> 00:17:54,893
This is such a nightmare.

307
00:17:55,806 --> 00:17:59,032
Okay, so we agree? This goes
back to Lily wanting to camp out

308
00:17:59,037 --> 00:18:01,030
for a wedding dress?

309
00:18:01,048 --> 00:18:04,152
No.
Wait. It goes back further.

310
00:18:04,166 --> 00:18:07,102
Remember why we were eating
hot dogs on the East Side?

311
00:18:17,186 --> 00:18:19,731
1939?!

312
00:18:20,205 --> 00:18:22,792
This penny's from 1939!

313
00:18:24,435 --> 00:18:27,580
A 67-year-old penny.

314
00:18:27,595 --> 00:18:30,511
Do you realize this penny was
minted during World War II?

315
00:18:30,526 --> 00:18:33,840
Oh, so was my grandfather,
but that doesn't make him interesting.

316
00:18:34,128 --> 00:18:36,451
Look, I know a little
something about coins,

317
00:18:36,468 --> 00:18:38,690
and this baby is worth
something to a collector.

318
00:18:38,707 --> 00:18:40,841
- No, it's not.
- Yes, it is!

319
00:18:40,855 --> 00:18:45,083
You know what?
I'm gonna take you out to dinner
with the money I get
for this little guy.

320
00:18:45,095 --> 00:18:47,352
<i>And that's exactly what I did.</i>

321
00:18:47,367 --> 00:18:50,971
You're lucky there's still a place that
serves anything for a dollar fifty.

322
00:18:50,987 --> 00:18:54,040
Hey, that's 150 times
its original value.

323
00:18:54,075 --> 00:18:57,591
Actually, the meal
was only $1.49.

324
00:18:58,496 --> 00:19:00,112
1984.

325
00:19:00,126 --> 00:19:02,920
Hey, in 50 years,
we can get dinner again.

326
00:19:03,028 --> 00:19:04,882
How dare you.

327
00:19:04,825 --> 00:19:06,792
Hey, what's going on?

328
00:19:06,407 --> 00:19:08,383
I don't know. Looks like they're
camping out for something.

329
00:19:08,117 --> 00:19:09,883
Yeah, but for what?

330
00:19:10,176 --> 00:19:11,912
It was me.

331
00:19:11,926 --> 00:19:14,012
I started this.

332
00:19:13,775 --> 00:19:15,742
If I hadn't picked
up that penny,

333
00:19:15,756 --> 00:19:18,520
we wouldn't have gone to get hot
dogs all the way across town.

334
00:19:18,537 --> 00:19:20,980
And we wouldn't have seen
that wedding dress store,

335
00:19:20,996 --> 00:19:22,941
Lily wouldn't have wanted
to camp out there,

336
00:19:22,957 --> 00:19:26,161
and I wouldn't have needed a nap
at your apartment the next day.

337
00:19:26,175 --> 00:19:28,422
Marshall wouldn't
have broken his toe.

338
00:19:28,456 --> 00:19:30,582
Barney wouldn't have
run the marathon.

339
00:19:30,597 --> 00:19:32,603
I wouldn't have jumped
that turnstile,

340
00:19:32,616 --> 00:19:35,122
gotten arrested,
had that court date...

341
00:19:35,205 --> 00:19:37,300
And we would have
made our flight.

342
00:19:37,858 --> 00:19:39,881
I don't think we can go
back any further than that

343
00:19:39,897 --> 00:19:42,032
unless you know who
dropped the penny.

344
00:19:41,647 --> 00:19:43,060
I wish I did.

345
00:19:43,077 --> 00:19:45,163
Though that person's already
been punished enough,

346
00:19:45,198 --> 00:19:47,663
losing a sweet penny like that.

347
00:19:49,646 --> 00:19:52,251
Oh,  please tell me you
have some good news.

348
00:19:52,265 --> 00:19:54,063
Uh, I'm afraid not.

349
00:19:54,078 --> 00:19:57,430
There are no extra
seats on the plane.
I'm sorry.

350
00:19:57,445 --> 00:19:59,502
All, right, well,
thanks for trying.

351
00:20:00,105 --> 00:20:03,811
I can't believe this.
That's it, it's over.

352
00:20:03,825 --> 00:20:05,632
Ted, come on.

353
00:20:05,646 --> 00:20:09,023
Your destiny just wasn't to
make it to Chicago today.

354
00:20:09,038 --> 00:20:11,970
Anyway, if that firm really wants you,
they'll reschedule.

355
00:20:12,325 --> 00:20:15,652
<i>But that's not what happened.
They didn't reschedule.</i>

356
00:20:15,668 --> 00:20:17,532
<i>They hired someone else.</i>

357
00:20:17,547 --> 00:20:20,081
<i>And as it turned out,
three months later,</i>

358
00:20:20,097 --> 00:20:23,372
<i>that guy ended up having
to relocate to Chicago.</i>

359
00:20:23,628 --> 00:20:25,761
Kids, funny thing
about destiny--

360
00:20:25,776 --> 00:20:28,241
I thought I was destined
to get that job.

361
00:20:28,258 --> 00:20:29,772
But I was wrong.

362
00:20:29,787 --> 00:20:32,151
My destiny was to
stay in New York.

363
00:20:32,486 --> 00:20:34,410
Because if I hadn't,

364
00:20:34,428 --> 00:20:36,570
I never would have
met your mother.

365
